{"kind":"textbox","id":"sh/idwfepsj","slide":3,"name":"code-conclusion","text":"The client cannot create gaps or conflicting versions.","textPreview":"The client cannot create gaps or conflicting versions.","textChars":54,"textLines":1,"bbox":[842,615,350,42]}
{"kind":"image","id":"im/obq5wnud","slide":3,"name":"","alt":"Python function that creates an immutable data source version snapshot","bbox":[42,150,758,504]}
{"kind":"notes","id":"nt/txlf66","slide":3,"text":"About 60 seconds. This is the core function from my implementation. First, select_for_update locks the parent data source while the transaction is running, so concurrent requests cannot allocate the same number. Next, the backend compares the current state with the latest snapshot. If nothing meaningful changed, it returns the existing version and avoids a duplicate. Otherwise, it calculates the next version number and stores the complete snapshot. The client never controls the number, so it cannot create gaps or conflicts."}
